{"/service/ndnp/fu/batch_fu_immokalee_ver01/data/sn95047334/00529042474/1958032701/0174.xml":{"full_text":"PAGE FOUR\nGADSDEN COUNTY TIMES\nand continuing\nTHE CHATTAHOOCHEE TRIBUNE\nPublished each Thursday at 15 S. Madison Street\nA JOHN H. PERRY NEWSPAPER\nESTABLISHED 1901\nQuincy, Florida\nEntered in the post office at Quincy. Florida, under the Act of\nMarch 1879 aa matter ot the second class\nOne Year, $3.00 Two Years, $5.50 Six Months, L 75\nI. L. Hutchinson Publisher\n\u00a9NATIONAL EDITORIAL\nT hIHMIMMMUIMM\nOn Losing U. S. Planes\nAnother U. S. Air Force aircraft has been shot down by\nthe Communists. The latest incident occurred in Korea, very\nclose to the demilitarized zone which divides South Korea\nand North Korea.\nHowever, the American aircraft shot down, an F-86 Sabre\njet, was shot down by anti-aircraft which would indicate\nthat it was going astray. Another Sabrejet was almost shot\ndown by the enemy anti-aircraft fire.\nU. S. aircraft are involved in too many \"incidents\" with\nCommunist defenses. The Communists are certainly to\nblame for shooting down our aircraft, such as their bar\nbarism of August, 1956, when sixteen Americans died in a\nNavy patrol plane shot down by the Chinese Communists.\nHowever, our planes are not always where they should\nbe, and this is the cause of some of the trouble. No doubt\nthe Communists, as well as our own air force, are constantly\nseeking reconnaissance photographs and reconnaissance\nInformation from \"across the border.\"\nOn training flights, however, there is little excuse for us\nviolating Communist territory. When our aircraft are shot\ndown by enemy anti-aircraft fire, it is obvious that they are\ntrespassing somewhat, or at least taking an unnecessary\nchance, since Communist anti-aircraft guns cannot operate\nanywhere except on Communist territory.\nWhile we regret to see U. S. airmen killed, because they\nfly on or too near Communist territory, that dos not excuse\nCommunist brutality in the killing of these airmen. But that\nis a barbarism with which we are quite familiar, and ample\nallowance for this ruthlessness should be made when trains\ning missions are involved.\nWe have no quarrel with Air Force officers if they wish\nto take a calculated risk for Intelligence or reconnaissance\npurposes. On training flights, however, it would seem that\nmore caution should be observed, or more protection af\nforded. When our planes are shot down by enemy fighters,\nwe have suggested that they be defended, and that they\ncarry their own fighter escort. When they are shot down\nby ground fire, however, the conclusion is almost inescap\nable that they were flying too close to Communist guns, on\nCommunist territory.\nManufacturers Speak\nAs every woman is well aware, and most men, for that\nmatter, the life-span of nylon stockings these days is a\nmajor concern, and a major threat to the budget of most\nAmerican families. However, the stocking manufacturer\nsays this is not the fault of the makers of these stockings.\nThe manufacturer, who becomes the target of dissatis\nfied citizens quite often, claims that today's sheer nylons\nare fragile because they are manufactured to suit the taste\nand fancies of the average female wearer. In other words,\nft is said that women demand sheer stockings, and that if\nthe manufacturer makes a tough nylon stocking, which is\nnot quite as sheer as another, the tougher, heavier-fabric\nstocking will not sell. Of course, in a free enterprise system\nsuch as ours, no one can expect a manufacturer to produce\na greater value if the public does not recognize it and will\nnot buy it.\nThe manufacturers believe they are unfairly criticized for\nbowing to the demand they have encountered in the mark\net. In short, they lay the blame for today's short-lived sheer\nnylons on the shoulders of those who demand such sheer\nstockings, inevitably subject to various sources of premature\ndestruction.\nIt may be that buyers of stockings will heed this word to\nthe wise and improve the situation. In any event, it is an\ninteresting light shed on a condition which, justifiably,\ncauses despair among millions of American women.\nIt is good to hear from the industry, and whatever the\ncause, many an American male paying his family's bills\nmonthly would welcome a little more life expectancy in\nthe average wear of nylon stockings. The working girl, and\nthose ladies who pay their own bills, would heartily join in\nthe approval of the above statement, and perhaps they may\nnow be able to do something about it in their choice of\nstockings.\nNixon's Timing\nVice-President Richard Nixon's call for a substantial\nacross-the-board tax cut, if the economy fails to show an\nupturn in the next few weeks, was a shrewd political stroke.\nWe do not infer that the Vice-President intended his move\nonly as a political one.\nHowever, the political repercussions were inevitable, and\nit must be admitted that the Vice-President's timing was\nmasterful. The Vice-President must be given credit for\nsincere concern with the nation's economic progress, and\nmust be credited with making a genuine effort to effect a\nrecovery through tax cuts.\nNevertheless, the Vice-President stole a march on the\nDemocrats, who had been the leading advocates of tax\nreductions early in the second session of the 85th Congress.\nHowever, as tax revenues fell below expectations, and de\nfense expenditurs were consistently higher than last year's\nestimates, congressional advocates of a tax cut saw the\nground cut steadily from beneath them.\nAlthough sentiment had swelled in Congress, among\nRepublicans and Democrats, in favor of a tax cut, the Vice-\nPresident's move was a major political breakthrough. More\nover, his reasoning and his full statement made a strong\nimpression on newspapers and citizens everywhere. The\nVice-President is undoubtedly profiting from the wisdom of\nnot speaking out too often on major issues, but having\nsomething to say when he does discuss issues vital to the\nnational economy.\nBut, more than this, the Vice-President's announcement\nwas a tip-off that the Administration may have been opti\nmistic in predicting an upturn as early as March. It may be\neven a hint to President Eisenhower himself that the Ad\nministration must make its anti-recession moves ahead of\ntime, and not follow events, so to speak, with corrections\nafter the event.\nThe President, meanwhile, is waiting another thirty days\nbefore making a final judgment\nWashingion\nReport\nBy Spessard Holland\nMack Case \u2014The resignation\nof Richard Mack as a member\nof the Federal Communications\nCommission, at the request of\nthe White House, has saddened\nall members of the Washington\nFlorida colony. The hearings be\nfore the Harris Subcommittee of\nthe House which is investigating\nFCC and the Grand Jury por\nceediftgs are both actively pend\ning. As one of those who strong\nly recommended Richard for this\nappointment and in justice to all\nconcerned I shall make a state\nment in the Senate for inclusion\nin the permanent Congressional\nRecord when the hearings have\nConcluded as to him, or at such\nearlier time as may seem appro\npriate.\nSoil Bank Amendment In\nthe effort to eliminate an obvious\ninjustice to farmers of several\nWest Florida counties, and coun\nties of other States which have\nrecently been designated for the\nfirst time as \u201ccommercial\u201d corn\nproducing counties, I introduced\nlast week an Amendment to the\nSoil Bank Act. The bill prohibits\nthe imposition of penalties on\nfarmers in such counties who,\nprior to January 1, had entered\ninto Conservation Contracts with\nthe government principally for\nreforestation and who, under the\npresent law, would be heavily\npenalized on those contracts for\nfailure to comply with the acre\nage allotment provisions of the\ncorn price support program.\nThese Conservation Reserve\nContracts were entered into in\ngood faith by the farmers and I\nao not feel there should be any\nconnection between these con\ntracts and corn acreage allot\nments which did not apply to\nthese counties when the con\ntracts were executed. I was join\ned in introducing the Amend\nment by Senators Russell, Hill,\nEastland, Talmadge, Sparkman,\nScott and Stennis. The USDA\nhas assured me of its support of\nthe measure, which has been\nfavorably reported by the Senate\nAgriculture Committee of which\nI am a member.\nExtra Soil Bank Funds \u2014The\nsecond supplemental appropria\ntion bill passed by the Senate\nlast Tuesday night carried with\nit a $250 million increase in\nacreage reserve soil bank bene\nfits. This will admit to the pro\ngram many additional farmers\nwho had been shut out because\nof the excess of applications over\navailable funds. This restores\nthat surplus removal program to\nits authorized size.\nHousing Bill Passed \u2014Liberal\nization of the National Housing\nAct and the Servicemen\u2019s Re\nadjustment Act, when the House\nconcurs, will be accomplished\nby a bill passed by the Senate at\na night session last Wednesday.\nThe measure is designed to sti\nmulate the lagging housing in\ndustry and to make it possible\nfor many families to acquire\nhomes on favorable terms.\nAmong other things this bill\nincreases the maximum interest\nrate on GI and VA home mort\ngages from 4i to 4-3/4% j\u2019extends\nthe VA home loan guaranty and\ndirect loan programs two years\nto July 25, 1960; provides an ex\ntra $1 billion for the FNMA to\nbuy FHA and VA mortgages on\nnew homes where the loan does\nnot exceed $13,500; provides an\nextra $5OO million for FNMA to\nbuy mortgages at the President\u2019s\ndiscretion if the recession wors\nens; adds an extra $l5O million\nfor direct VA loans in each of\nthe next two fiscal years, and\n$5O million for each quarter of\nthe peresent fiscal year remain\ning unexpired on the date of fin\nal enactment of the bill; adds\n$5O million for FNMA purchase\nof military housing mortgages\nand lowers down payments on\nFHA loans to 3% on the first\n$13,500 of mortgage (now 3% on\nfirst $10,000).\nPublic Works Speed-Up \u2014The\nSenate acted this week to com\nbat the economic recession by\npassing a resolution calling for\nstepped-up civil works construc\ntion. The accelerated program\nwould apply only to projects for\nwhich Congress has already ap\npropriated funds. It is estimated\nthat approximately $4 billion in\nunexpended funds are involved.\nSimilar action is expected soon\nwith reference to military public\nworks projects.\nThis action represents only the\nbegining. of a much broader at\ntack on the business slump. It\nexpresses the \u201csense of Congress\u201d\nthat something should be done\nabout the situation now as op\nposed to any \u201cwait and see\u2019 at\ntitude.\nGADSDEN COUNTY TIMES, QUINCY, FLORIDA, THURSDAY, MARCH 27, 1958\nMISSILE SITES SOUGHT\nThe United States, having com\npleted arrangements for nuclear\nmissile bases in the British Isles,\nis now negotiating for similar\nlaunching sites in France.\nGen. Lauris Norstad, NATO\u2019s\nEuropean commander, in a re\ncent statement, said that while\npreliminary discussions have\nbeen started with France for\nbases there, no specific agree\nment has been reached so far.\nLETTER TO SOVIETS BACKED\nCongress has rallied strongly\nbehind President Eisenhower in\nhis recent tough letter to Soviet\nPremier Nikolai A. Bulganin on\nholding a summit meeting.\nEisenhower in effect told Bul\nganin to show whether he really\nwanted a meeting or just a pro\npaganda fight. He called for\nless publicized contacts mean\ning lower East-West talks to\ntry to arrange a meeting.\nU. S. STILL IMPORTING\nThe current recession has a\nnew international twist. While\nslackened foreign buying has\nadded to the business slump here,\nthe slump has not cut into the\nvolume of American buying of\nforeign goods.\nOfficials here expect no pos\nitive anti-recession aid from\nabroad in the form of increased\nforeign buying here, but some\nexpect that the downward trend\nwill soon halt.\nPROTESTS MOUNT\nPentagon proposals for reduc\ning the strength of the Army Na\ntional Guard have let loose a\nflash flood of protests.\nIt appears that Congress? will\nnot permit a reduction in these\nreserve forces unless a conclu\nsive showing is made that it will\nproduce a stronger retaliative\nfiring power in the event of an\nattack.\nI //Hl\nI/\nRoad-leveling 124* wheelbase on\nI Super Chief and Star Chief.\nIndustry\u2019s most advanced V-g\u2014\nZ'\"JR Tempest 395\u20140 n every model\ni at extra att\nIndustry\u2019s widest selection of\nlong-lasting Lucite lacquer on\nStar Chief and Ronneiille\nat no extra cost.\nSmoother riding oversize tires on\nWish You Could Afford This Beauty? .===_\nYou can\u2014it\u2019s America\u2019s Number Value! if you\u2019ve had your eye on this\nbig, bold action car\u2014well, just stop dreaming and price it! You\u2019re in for a very\nhappy surprise... a surprise matched only by the thrill of your first exciting\nturn behind the wheel. And when you see all that Pontiac gives you as standard Genuine top-grain leather\non Star Chief and Bonneville\nequipment you 11 agree that it s today s biggest money s worth! models at no extra cost.\nGet the FACTS f IVT IT A America\u2019s Number (J)\nand You\u2019ll Get a_LVzi 1 J- X2a_ V Road Car\ng^pi^Giese in asset wMms SEE YOUR LOCAL AUTHORIZED PONTIAC DEALER\nFRYER-SMITH MOTOR CO.\n112 E. JEFFERSON STREET QUINCY\nE. H. S. REPORTS\nFROM WASHINGTON\nTax Cui Coming?\nSentiment Snowballs\nInterest Going Down\nCar Cuts Coming?\nWashington The continued\nrecession has caused a ground\nswell of sentiment in Congress,\namong Republicans as well as\nDemocrats, for a tax cut which\nwould become effective July Ist,\nOctober Ist or January Ist.\nChances seem surprisingly good\nthat the earliest date may be\npicked.\nThe President has hinted, on\nearlier occasions, that this month\nshould see the upturn in the\neconomy so many have been\nlooking for, but there is grave\ndoubt as to that at the moment.\nThe Administration is not idle to\nthe threat, but whether it is\nmoving in front of the tide or\nbehind it, is a question hotly de\nbated on Capitol Hill these days.\nThe President\u2019s advisors are\nfor lowering interest rates,\nspeeding defense orders es\npecially in hard-hit areas, lower\ning mortgage requirements, and\nlowering taxes, if necessary. In\naddition public works projects\nwill be initiated on a larger\nscale.\nVice President Nixon is gen\nerally credited with a masterful\njob of political timing in com\ning out for a tax cut. His call\ncame at a time when there was\nevident concern in both parties,\nand among the populace, and re\nceived a fine reception.\nOf course, in all the talk about\ntax cuts, it should be remember\ned that this is a congressional\nelection year. That fact alone en\nhances chances of enactment at\nthis session, which is the last of\nthe 85th Congress.\nAmong Republicans, Nixon is\ncredited with having wrested the\nlead from the Democrats in the\ntax-cutting field. Although the\nDemocrats had assumed this lead\nearly in this session, and did\nmost of the speculating on tax\ncuts, the Administration made it\nclear just a couple of short\nmonths ago that no tax cut\nwould be supported. As an in\ndication how much the situation\nhas deteriorated, one can con\ntrast the present attitude, espe\ncially of the Vice President, with\nthe official view of the Admini\nstration just a couple of months\nago.\nAs interest rates are cut\nafter a short spell at \u201chardship\u201d\nrates, home and office building\nwill become easier and borrow\ning may increase, if confidence\ndoes not continue to decline.\nThe auto makers, too, might\nbe affected. It\u2019s true that they\nhave hard bargaining from labor\non schedule in the coming\nmonths and that any great in\ncrease in labor costs will probab\nly eliminate the chance of a pric\ncut long overdue in the autc\nmotive field.\nBut reduction in taxes migt\nenable the automobile companie\nto announce decreases, while ex\ncise tax cuts might further re\nduce the price to the consumei\nThe consumer, aided by lowe\ntaxes himself, might respond t<\nlower cost automobiles, in turn.\nAnd the automobile business is\nabout the biggest consumer busi\nness in the country.\nTherefore, the present picture\nmight be one of some encourage\n'ment. If excise taxes, in addi\njtion to business and personal in\ncome taxes, are reduced, the year\n1958 might have proved to be\nmemorable and the second ses\nsion of the 85th Congress might\nhave taken the only action possi\nble to prolong its individual\nlives.\nMembers are definitely upset\nabout business, our defense pro\ngram, and future developments\nin these fields.\nWashington, Mar. 4 \u2014The\nslim margin of victory racked\nup by Republican Albert Quie\nover Democrat Eugene Foley in\nMinnesota\u2019s formerly rock-rib\nbed Republican First District,\nFebruary 17, lends blunt empha\nsis to Democratic predictions that\nthe country is ready for a change\nin government.\nQuie, a dairy farmer and a\nstate senator, was expected to\nswamp Foley, a 29-year-old law\nyer who had never held public\noffice, but it didn\u2019t turn out that\nway. Quie eked by with a mar\ngin of 655 votes in a district that\nhas gone solidly Republican\nsince 1893.\nHow did a Democratic novice\nmanage to poll an amazing 43,655\nvotes to his GOP oponents .44,-\n310 in such a Republican strong\nhold? Foley credits his showing\nwith his all-out attack on the\npolicies of Secretary of Agricul\nture Ezra Taft Benson the\nnumber one whipping boy for the\nDemocrats in the farm belt.\nBut it may go deeper than that\nQuie also lashed the policies of\nMr. Benson during the cam\npaign, expressing particular op\nposition to his scheduled dairy\nprice support cut and other ad\nministration 7 backed farm pro\ngrams considered vastly unpopu\nlar in his part of the country.\nWhy,then, should the Demo\ncrats have nearly captured a\nstaunchly Republican seat when\nthe Democratic and Republican\ncandidates both fired at the same\ntarget, and took familiar sides\non the same issues?\nThe answer may lie in Presi\ndent Eisenhower\u2019s stubborn de\nfense of his farm Secretary, and\nhis refusal to alter Benson\u2019s\npolicies, even at the frantic urg\ning of many congressmen and\nsenators high in the GOP ranks.\nPerhaps the farmers are begin\ning to feel that the only way\nthey\u2019ll get rid of Benson is to\nget rid of the whole Republican\nadministration.\nK7I I\nREMOVES 7i|^ |k!\nRUST STAINS\nfrM BATHTUBS' SINKS\nCOPPER POTS TILE\n1\nHULjww\u00dfXiliiuLl^^^Guf^w\nRUHAIN PRODUCTS,\nfAIRUWN,N.X \u00bbo.m\u2014\nWhether this is the answer, or\nwhether it lies in more complex\ntheories as Republicans in\nWashington are quick to argue\n\u2014the Minnesota election scared\nthe daylights out of many a GOP\nsolon in whose state the Demo\ncratic-Republican vote is more\nprecariously balanced.\nThey are asking themselves\nnow, \u201cIf the Democrats can make\nsuch powerful showing in a dis\ntrict as dyed-iruthe wool Repub\nlican as Minnesota\u2019s first, what\nmight not they do in my district?\nThe upshot of it will prob\nably be a renewed drive by the\nRepublican legislators for Secre\ntary Benson's political scalp\ngreater demands for his resig\nnation and a strengthening of\nopposition in the Republican\nranks to Benson's farm legisla\ntion proposals.\nGERMAN REUNIFICATION\nBonn, Germany The Soviet\nproposal for reuniting Germany\nby confederating the West and\nEast German states is gaining\nacceptance among West German\npoliticians.\nIn a number of interviews and\nspeeches some political leaders\nhave indicated a willingness to\nexamine the Soviet idea, though\nit is still officially repudiated by\ntheir organizations.\nUse the Classified ad section.\nSAFEGUARD\nYO\\|R CLOTHES\nStunning appearance depends\nupon smart clothes. Keep your\nclothes smart longer the Sunshine\nway- the sure way of preserving\nthe woolens and silks you cherish.\ngAjpUUHP suSSkm-\nVyLAUNORY^\nExercise is what your friend\nshould take to get rid of the\nmiddle-aged spread.\n\nAdvertising is the difference\nbetween many big businesses and\nsmaller ones.\nI W\nI\nSUBER JOHNSON CO.\n21S W. Jefferson Quincy","height":"29160","width":"20151"}}
